# A type of [[Unsorted/Rocks\|rock]] formed when a parent rock (protolith) is changed in form, typically through increases in heat and/or pressure

### Metamorphism can...
- ...result from increases in heat and/or pressure
- ...only be done on solid rocks


## Entymology
- **Meta-**: change
- **-morphic**: form


# Metamorphosis

- ## Types of metamorphosis:
	- ##### Recrystallization
		- Vacancies within the crystal structures of minerals allow atoms to migrate through the crystal structure
			- At higher temperatures, the bonds weaken, allowing them to re-bond in other places
			- Does nnot destroy the integrity of the solid
		- Occurs when:
			- rock is heated in the hot regions of solid rock surrounding [[Unsorted/Volcanism#^3b4c3e\|magma chambers]]
			- Groundwater carries heat past solid rock
			- Seawater seeps into hacks around mid ocean ridges, and interacts with deep rock
		- Effects:
			- Increases the size of minerals
			- Alters cementation material
				- Can be reincorporated, remain between minerals, or chemically escape
		- Example: Quartz sandstone
			- Originally has a clastic texture
			- Turns into a crystalline texture as neighboring clasts merge into larger crystals
	- ##### Neocrystallization
		- Growth of new minerals within protoliths
		- Change in chemical composition
			- The component minerals of the rock are chemically altered
			- When conditions are right, can be reversed


- ## Factors and causes of metamorphosis

- ### Temperature
	- Most important type, because it enables recrystallization
- ### Pressure (stress)
	- 2 types:
		- Confining pressure
			- Equal forces coming from all directions
			- Results in very densely-packed minerals
		- Differential stress
			- AKA directed pressure
			- Imbalanced stress in different directions
			- Results in flattened/elongated minerals
				- Flattening happens on axis of net pressure
				- Elongation happens along 
- ### Hydrothermal activity
	- Interaction with hot fluids
		- ...because it often happens at hydrothermal vents
	- Also happens around mid-ocean ridges
	- Process
		- Cool water seeps through cracks in the Earth
		- The water interacts with hot rocks near magma chambers
		- The heated water rises up through other cracks, and is expelled from hydrothermal vents
- ### Protolith composition
	- Can only form metamorphic rocks that are derived from the protolith present

# Classification

### Features
- Foliation
	- Layers and bands due to differential pressure/stress
	- Separates metamorphic rocks into 2 primary types:
		- Foliated
			- Can be difficult to see in rocks with large grains
			- But can still be identified by color-banding
		- Non-foliated
	- Non-foliated
		- No visible layering
- Composition
	- Influenced by recrystallization
- Grain size
	- Porphyroblasts
		- Unusually large grains in metamorphic rocks, typically foliated

##### Foliated metamorphic rocks
- Formed via recrystallization on rocks with different amounts of pressure on each axis
	- Differential stress at continental-continental plate boundaries

- [[Hornfels\|Hornfels]]
	- A general name used for contact metamorphic rocks that are nonfoliated and too fine grained for individual minerals to be readily recognized.
	- Protoliths such as shale is baked by the intense heat from the intrusion of magma body and metamorphosed into hornfels. 
	- Contact Aureole refers to the zone of intense metamorphism immediately surrounding the magma body.

# Metamorphic Environments


- ### Contact metamorphism
	- AKA Thermal metamorphism
		- Word "Contact" is confusing since it implies pressure
	- Heat driven, not pressure driven
		- Produces non-foliated metamorphic rocks
	- Occurs in bodies of rock surrounding [[Unsorted/Volcanism#^3b4c3e\|Volcanism#^3b4c3e]]
	- magma chambers
- ### Regional metamorphism
	- Happens at **collision zones** and **subduction zones**
	- Subtypes
		- Collision zone metamorphism
			- Continental-continental convergence
			- The source of all foliated metamorphic rockscollision zones
				- Higher-grade foliated metamorphic rocks form at the root of the mountain
		- Subduction zone metamorphism
			- Oceanic-continental or oceanic-oceanic convergence
			- Material from the surface of oceanic plates is very cool and dense
				- So it does not heat up that much while being subducted
				- Results in an accretionary prism of blueschist
- ### Hydrothermal metamorphism
	- Chemical change due to circulating, hot, iron-rich water
	- Occurs at divergent plate boundaries
	- "Serpentinization": Turns igneous rock into metamorphic rock
		- Can also occur on land through [[Unsorted/groundwater\|groundwater]]
- ### Fault zone metamorphism
	- Along active fault lines
	- Contains unique metamorphic rocks
		- Broken-up surface rocks: "Fault breccia"
		- Forms Mylonite at depth
			- Due to plastic deformation of fault breccia, causing each rock to become extremely elongated
			- Plastic deformation occurs when temperature is high enough
- ### Impact (shock) metamorphism
	- Occurs at the site of meteorite impacts
	- Seriously effects rocks
		- Some are vaporized
		- 
	- Forms "Impactites"
		- Impcat breccia
		- Tektites
			- Stream-like rods of rock
		- Shocked quartz
			- Looks scorched
	- Impactites have higher iridium content than surrounding rock
